==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Idyl
<hw>I"dyl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>idyllium</ets>,
Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ form; literally, a little form of image: cf. F.
<ets>idylle</ets>. See <er>Idol</er>.]</ety> <def>A short poem;
properly, a short pastoral poem; <as>as, the <ex>idyls</ex> of
Theocritus</as>; also, any poem, especially a narrative or descriptive
poem, written in an elevated and highly finished style; also, by
extension, any artless and easily flowing description, either in poetry
or prose, of simple, rustic life, of pastoral scenes, and the
like.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>idyll</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wordsworth's solemn-thoughted <qex>idyl</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His [Goldsmith's] lovely <qex>idyl</qex> of the Vicar's home.</q>
<rj><qau>F. Harrison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Idyllic</ent>⟦br⟧
